column2: Dale Johnston
column69: Hi there, I was going to empty the water out of my "yard waste" trash can but I heard something thrashing around in the water as I got close to the can.  The critter was really freaked out. I laid the can on its side but the lizard would not come out.  When I upended the can, it finally came running out on its hind legs and its "arms" out to the side.  I almost died laughing.  Sorry, no photo.  I think it was some kind of basilisk lizard, but it was a VERY dark green, almost black, with wide  gold or yellow markings running across the body, not along it as shown in photos i have seen online of brown basilisks.  Also remember that the lizard was soaking wet.  Feel sorry for the little guy as he could have been in the trash can for quite awhile.  If you need to contact me email is best. Do not call my cell # as it only works when I am at home in the US.  I can be reached by phone if need be at 561-832-8566, option 2 then dial ext. 4331.

column153: There are MANY more (adults and young) at this location in same neighborhood: 25.462884 / -80.449932. Location is SW 328th street along canal. I've seen them sunning on the sidewalk and in the shrubs on north side of canal (no doubt more along the canal on both sides but I haven't looked.) This was first time I've seen them away from the canal and inside the neighborhood. I live here --its a gated community. If anyone wanted to come inside to look, they can email me: lori_oberhofer@nps.gov. I suspect these things are all over, inside and outside the neighborhood, but have not been reported.

column153: Frilled lizard (chlamydosaurus) or brown basilisk lizard ran across the street directly in front of my car. 18 inches long, brown, running on hind legs, either had a large frill or ridge, no clear. Looked very much like a big showing frill to me, but I've never heard of frilled lizards here, and we do have basilisks. Sorry I did not stop and photo, will go back tomorrow and see if I can get pictures of the thing.

column153: An area along a creek just off a sidewalk in the condominium complex Beacon 21. I reported seeing this a couple of weeks ago, but I saw it (or another one) again today and was able to get a picture of it. It was near some water in our condominium complex here in Jensen Beach. The lizard's body was about 7 inches long, but its tail was VERY long - another foot or so. It stood up on its hind legs and ran away toward the creek.

column2: Jordan Marshall
column27: Personal Communication
column69: Jensen Beach, NE 14th Ct 353 m N of NE Dixie Hwy
column153: I was walking my dog in our condo complex in Jensen Beach, FL. She flushed out a large lizard that I had never seen before and it stood up on its 2 hind legs and ran. She chased it back and forth along a fence line for a minute or so, and I got a good look at it. That night I compared images from the Internet to what I had seen and there is no doubt that it was a brown basilisk. I have never seen a lizard run on its hind legs like that - and it was VERY fast. Unfortunately, I had no camera with me to take a picture of it.

column153: A window installer felt he saw nile monitors. I haven't seen anything I would consider a nile monitor. I have seen knight anoles and what I think was a chinese water dragon, and the three photos I've sent you of other lizards I can't identify. The first 2 were taken the same day this spring when 4 congregated on the driveway, with mating behavior. The third picture was taken last month of a large lizard on the lanai screen. I'd love to know what they are and if I should ignore them or not. I can confirm they have an active nest dug under the pool equipment's cement block and I think another in the front yard. Thanks very much for all you do.

column153: Phil Allman of FGCU examined the photo and commented: "The lizard looks like common basilisk, Basiliscus basiliscus but the striped basilisk (or brown basilisk), Basciliscus vittatus, has a similar appearance. Both species have been introduced to FL and can be locally abundant. The biggest difference between the two is that striped basilisks have a cream colored stripe extending down the dorsal edge of the body. I cannot see such a stripe in this photo so I assume it is common basilisk."
